events.body:
Thanks, I chedked that the key fingerprint `590B7292695AFFA5B672CBB2E13FC145CD3F4304` matches what is used to sign gitian releases.

Same as for #20846: I've been unable to get this key from keyservers, do you have it published somehwere?

It should be at `hkps://keys.openpgp.org` and `hkps://keyserver.ubuntu.com:443` (checking the other ones in my gpg.conf now).
I can probably dump it in --armor in the commit message ?

EDIT: It's also at `hkps://pgp.ocf.berkeley.edu`
EDIT 2: Added it in the commit message too.

> It should be at hkps://keys.openpgp.org

You'll need to verify your email with them to make it downloadable, I think

> EDIT 2: Added it in the commit message too.

I think putting it in the commit message is a good idea, though, I wouldn't clearsign the exported public key with the key itself. It seems a bit like putting scissors in a package that needs scissors to open 🙂
Is this is a case of the more the better with Gitian keys? Or are we happy with the number of these post merging this?

<!--e57a25ab6845829454e8d69fc972939a-->

The following sections might be updated with supplementary metadata relevant to reviewers and maintainers.

<!--174a7506f384e20aa4161008e828411d-->
### Conflicts
Reviewers, this pull request conflicts with the following ones:

* #20846 (Add benthecarman to keys.txt by benthecarman)

If you consider this pull request important, please also help to review the conflicting pull requests. Ideally, start with the one that should be merged first.

> Is this is a case of the more the better with Gitian keys? Or are we happy with the number of these post merging this?

This is a case of people who have been regularly performing gitian builds adding their keys to this file. See https://github.com/bitcoin-core/gitian.sigs/issues/1427.
